<p>Ecuador’s prosecutor’s office said it found no evidence that an Ecuadorian man who survived a U.S. military strike on a suspected drug‑trafficking submersible in the Caribbean had committed a crime, and he was released upon return to the country [abcnews.go.com#1][bbc.com#1][cbsnews.com#1][allsides.com#1][theguardian.com#1][firstpost.com#1]. U.S. forces had rescued the man following the strike before he was repatriated to Ecuador, where prosecutors declined to detain him [allsides.com#1][cbsnews.com#1]. The Trump administration alleged the vessel was transporting drugs, and President Trump referred to those aboard as “terrorists” [abcnews.go.com#1][theguardian.com#1].</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/7O1oOIHkJibvwZTSRI3VbSecSGltyjw6vktMiqbwRcBsFR8mC_iCcY_cLMZd4Kkoc-1OT2GbnURU12LgQThVvDVeV8XSbv5h2VjDwSXlxuQ1ka5CDMEJHd0HwqHQvPfNB_dvZFvNqTd5kMY' alt='Ecuador freed a survivor of a U.S. strike in the Caribbean after finding no evidence of a crime.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Regional campaign: Since August, the U.S. has deployed warships to the Caribbean off Venezuela, focusing strikes mainly on boats U.S. authorities said were running drugs [theguardian.com#1].</li><li>Intelligence role: Sources cited by the Guardian said the CIA is playing “the most important part” in the Caribbean strikes, indicating a heavy intelligence footprint behind operations [theguardian.com#1].</li><li>Return timeline: Officials said the survivor arrived back in Ecuador on Saturday before prosecutors reviewed his case [allsides.com#1][abcnews.go.com#1].</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Ecuador prosecutor’s office: Prosecutors said they had no evidence the man committed a crime and therefore released him. (<a href='https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cn97vl7vy7xo'>BBC News</a>)</li><li>U.S. government: Officials alleged the submersible was transporting drugs in the Caribbean. (<a href='https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/ecuador-evidence-survivor-us-strike-caribbean-committed-crime-126701528'>ABC News</a>)</li><li>President Trump: He called people on the submarine “terrorists.”. (<a href='https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/oct/21/ecuador-releases-survivor-us-strike-submarine'>The Guardian</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.allsides.com/news/2025-10-21-0700/americas-ecuador-says-no-evidence-detain-survivor-us-strike-suspected-drug-vessel'>Ecuador says no evidence to detain survivor of US strike on suspected drug vessel</a> - allsides.com</li><li><a href='https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/oct/21/ecuador-releases-survivor-us-strike-submarine'>Ecuador releases survivor of US strike on alleged drug-trafficking submarine</a> - theguardian.com</li><li><a href='https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/ecuador-evidence-survivor-us-strike-caribbean-committed-crime-126701528'>Ecuador says it has no evidence that survivor of a US strike in the Caribbean committed any crime</a> - abcnews.go.com</li><li><a href='https://www.firstpost.com/world/no-evidence-that-survivor-of-us-strike-in-caribbean-sea-committed-any-crime-says-ecuador-13943788.html'>No evidence that survivor of US strike in Caribbean Sea committed any crime, says Ecuador</a> - firstpost.com</li><li><a href='https://www.cbsnews.com/news/ecuador-releases-survivor-us-strike-narco-sub-no-evidence-crime/'>Ecuador releases survivor of U.S. strike on alleged &quot;narco sub&quot;</a> - cbsnews.com</li><li><a href='https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cn97vl7vy7xo'>Ecuador releases survivor of US strike on &#x27;drug sub&#x27; in Caribbean</a> - bbc.com</li></ul>